rComments: When I first signed up for this class I was very skeptical on how interesting a class on primates would be. Julie made the class super interesting and entertaining. The midterms and final were mostly based off lectures and class videos. Besides the 3 exams, there's also a short 3 page paper on a primate of ur choice.

Julie is an awesome professor! She creates a really engaging class environment and explains topics clearly. Her tests can be tricky but pay attention in lecture and study the slides and you're golden. I've taken three of her classes and LOVED each one. She's exactly what UCSC needs in the Physical Anthropology department!

For some reason, I thought she made the final extra hard..which bumped me down a grade. But she was a really nice and knowledgeable teacher. You definitely should go to class because she puts things she says in class that are not on the notes on the test!
Julie is a good, knowledgable professor. This class was pretty easy as long as you take good notes. Test material was from the lecture and videos, not too much from the reading. Light work load.

Omgosh this lady is AMAZING. She knows her stuff and she brings SO much to the lecture hall. More than just an hour and a half of notes. She makes jokes, laughs a lot, and is extremely passionate about her studies (she is a primatologist). I thoroughly enjoyed her class and made sure to tell her that after handing in my final. She is a real teacher

Julie is AMAZING! She's very passionate and knowledgeable about her work. Her exams are very fair, but you should read the textbook to reinforce the material you learned in lecture. She's Canadian and uses the CANADIAN grading system, which is so much more forgiving than America's. Unfortunately, she's only a visiting scholar and is leaving.
